Subject: Immuno-Labeling  elution  and re-labeling of ultra-thin cortical brain sections
Question: Several experiments were carried-out to determine the best method of antibody elution while preserving antigenicity of the ultra-thin plastic embedded sections.  Sections were stained with antibodies against the Vglut1  Synapsin  and Synaptobrevin antigens  followed by imaging with the IX81system.  Several different acidic buffers were used to elute the stain  and the sections were re-stained under the same conditions and imaged. Subject: Circuit for thresholding the analog signal (0-500 mV) and generate a digital output (trigger)
Question: The DC signal has a range of 0-500 mV. The circuit was fabricated  tested and delivered. The circuit consisted of a 10X gain stage and an op-amp based comparator stage. The power supply to be provided has to be regulated 5V DC. Input diodes were not available to minimize the input bias current for the op-amps so care must be taken. Op-Amps used were LM741 for comparator stage and MCP6291 for the gain stage.  http://www.national.com/mpf/LM/LM741.html  http://ww1.microchip.com/downloads/en/DeviceDoc/21812e.pdf    I have placed an order for AD790  which is a fast  precision comparator. We will use this specialized IC in future >> http://www.analog.com/static/imported-files/data_sheets/AD790.pdf  Digikey order for 10 AD790JN-ND IC PREC COMPARATOR HS 8-DIP  Unit price $9.08000  Total $90.80

Subject: Fabrication of a demux circuit for the shutter controller
Question: According to the camera hardware guide  the FIRE TTL output of the camera  which we would use as the input for your circuit  is some AC family logic circuit in series with 50 ohm. In principle that should be able to source 24 mA  judging from random AC family data sheets I found  which would satisfy the >5 mA that the TLP797J apparently requires. But the manual also says to load with >1 kOhm  which would not quite satisfy the TLP797J requirement. I?m unsure whether it would be a bad idea to load the camera output with the TLP797J (in series with 1 kOhm or so). We may be able to skip the optoisolation; the NM shutter drivers all have optoisolated inputs anyway  which should hopefully keep their considerable transients out of your part of the circuit. The only remaining purpose of optoisolation would be to prevent a ground loop involving the camera and computer  a problem that we could either ignore  or deal with simply by not connecting the ground wire of the FIRE input (and using isolated BNC connectors that don?t short the shield to the box).    I assume the hex gate you linked to was for the input OR-gate purpose? Unless I?m confused  it can?t source enough current to serve the output driver purpose. The MUX is active low  and the NM shutter drivers take active high input  so the MUX needs inverting drivers on the output. These have to be able to source at least 1.5 mA into {2 kOhm + 1V drop}  preferably with margin. How about a 74AC540 or equivalent?    I am leaning towards an arrangement where this MUX circuit and four of the NM shutter driver boards (the CX1100B ? yes the CX1100 data sheet you linked to is the correct one) share a single enclosure. Each CX1100 board contains its own AC power supply  which may be a bit silly that but could actually be helpful in preventing the large current spikes that each driver outputs from propagating to anywhere unwanted. These four drivers would use four of the possible outputs of the MUX. Assuming that we do have a spare DIO bit available on the NI card  we would route the remaining four MUX output channels to BNCs (via the inverting drivers)  for hypothetical future external shutter drivers. It would be slightly useful (but not crucial) to include the polarity toggles we talked about for these channels. For the NM channels polarity toggle are of course not needed  because we know the required polarity already. If there are no toggles  the polarity for the BNC outputs should be active high  like the NM channels. If there is no spare DIO bit available  we?d just eliminate the BNC channels and go with the 4 NM channels.    The CX1100 drivers would drive LST200 shutters. These have cables with a strange 3-pin connector on the end. NM says the mating bulkhead connector is SwitchCraft Mini-C2 TY3F  and they have already sent off four of these directly to you via UPS 3-day (for the outputs of the NM drivers).    As you saw in the data sheet  the CX1100 has several utility connections  some of which we should make use of:    LED S     Drives an LED to indicate shutter active. We should implement this LED  for each channel.     TBLOCK   Interlock. We should route these to a terminal block on the front panel  to allow interlocking if necessary.    LED Power    Indicates power on.  We could implement this LED on one channel to indicate power on for the whole box? But you wanted to power your section separately  so it may need its own power-on LED?    LED Armed   Indicates armed condition.  We should implement this LED  for each channel.    +5 V DC      Do not use    SWITCH      Opens shutter regardless of input. Should be wired to a front panel toggle switch for each channel.    PUSH          Resets the driver to armed condition after power out etc. Should be routed to a momentary-contact push button (per channel?).    Four drivers take a lot of room. Can they be stacked in pairs?    AC to the drivers should come via a standard AC cord connector (on back)  a fuse (?)  and an on/off toggle switch (preferably on the front). Since AC is supplied  the 5V for your logic should probably come from a supply inside the box. The driver boards do supply 5V  but I don?t want to use it for upstream logic  because doing so would defeat their internal optoisolation.

Tech note: 03/16/2009    Ses Lin's email on 03/15/2009 (Sunday)    Hi Xiaorong and Kevin      Because most of sequences failed from the RCA request on March 12th (results see folder 2009-03-14-0148  0149  0150).  I started growing cultures of all 48 samples (A1-H1  A2-H2  A3-H3  A4-H4  A5-H5  A6-H6) today and please do a miniprep on Monday and then sequencing again with Lin 0.5f.  The plate is growing in our small incubator next to the cold room.  (I just changed temp from 37 to 30).  Kevin  could you also send my minis to ?Genewiz? as well just in case the sequencing fail again. Thanks.     Lin        ------ Forwarded Message  From: "McGowan  Kevin M." <mcgowank@janelia.hhmi.org>  Date: Sun  15 Mar 2009 12:43:27 -0400  To: Janelia Farm <tianl@janelia.hhmi.org>  Subject: your sequences from the weekend    Lin     I took a look at your sequencing reactions from the weekend and they are mostly bad. I tried to get you some extra basecalls on them by reextracting the data using a less stringent analysis protocol. You will see in your folder a new folder called ?reanalysis of 3-14-09? or something like that. The reanalysis is done with very low quality score threshold so please be careful in interpreting the results. Please also note that I did not rename the samples when I reanalyzed them  I just put them into a different folder.    The failed sequences appear to have high background ( a lot of noise)  which can come from poor priming or template contamination. The ones that do look OK  a few of them stop prematurely like maybe the sequence is GC rich. My recommendation would be to send these reactions to our contract company  Genewiz  and see if they can do a better job of it. We can arrange the samples for shipping  if you like. We have a protocol for GC-rich samples that may help with the ones that have worked; if you would like us to run this subset using this protocol let me know.     Kevin

Subject: Wrapping up Intan
Question: Consulting with anthony about the existing intan circuit and voltage offsets that may inhibit recording fidelity.    Background  documentation of existing system  research  and discussions

Subject: Discuss the issues with Intan
Question: I've messed around with the intan board for a few days. We are still having some drift problems  and ID&F assistance would be very valuable in solving them. My lab can be used for testing  if this is helpful. To begin I'd like to summarize the symptoms:    (1) 60-ch ITO electrode array  electrodes coated with TiN to ~1.0-1.5MOhm impedances (10um electrodes). in this config we have electrodes sitting in saline.  	(a) in RSE mode (Vdiff->Agnd)  electrode voltages drift to  	 ~1.3V DC offset out of intan chips; 30uV bg noise. note that amps run to +-2.5V  so this is not saturated.  	(b) in diff mode  electrodes close to 0V DC  ~10uV RMS (note I am giving DC offset in amp output levels  and RMS noise in gain-adjusted electrode levels).    In RSE mode  signal generator input S+ applied directly to one electrode pin (w/ S- to gnd) looks to be the expected voltage. so signals are getting through.    (2) MUX gnd has 20 Ohm impedance to rack adjacent to rig. swapping "analog gnd" (to table  cage  array) between rack and MUX does not have much effect. the difference in gnd potential between the rack and the intan board is slightly troubling  because (for example) if i bring in another input to the nidaq which is at rack gnd (eg a photodiode) there is now a potential for mixing of gnds signals. there concern along these lines is that perhaps this is already happening somehwere in the system.   But again  this may not be pertinant to the drift problem.    So it is essentially RSE mode where we have problems (both drift and RMS noise level)  which is puzzling.  It could be that V+ and Vdiff are drifting together  but it is not clear why this would be the case. If I swap out the electrode array and put in a test circuit that grounds  V+ to V- via a 200KOhm resistor  all problems seem to vanish (no DC offsets in diff or RSE; rms noise of 5uV and 7uV  respectively).    There are known drift problems (seen by various collaborators) with these intan amplifiers with certain electrode types; these are hypothesized to be due to electrochemical effects at the electrode interface. Example -- silicon probes work poorly  tungsten electrodes work well. Impedance does not appear to be the issue.  This is all anecdotal. There are also options w/ altering the composition of our electrodes if electrochemistry is the problem.    Long story short -- the problem here may very well be due to the ultra low cutoff of the intan chips  perhaps in combo with our array electrodes. Reid has suggested sticking a high pass filter on at the electrode pin (pre-intan)  and it may be that this + some digitial hpf will solve the problem. We need to pin the problems to either the intans or the board. It would be great if we could scrutinize the design of the MUX board very closely  both to see if there are any obvious errors but also to determine if we can add in any aux circuity to ameliorate the problem if they are at the intan level.    I suggest we brainstorm a bit today on options  and then maybe get together in the lab tomorrow morning to try some things.    I appreciate the help!    anthony      ps.    A few minor comments from Reid on the board layout (again  prob not relevant but I pass them along as an FYI):     >>  (1) You might reduce the crosstalk you're seeing if you buffered the analog output signals before the cable and NI board.  As I mentioned earlier  I think that's probably a bit too much capacitance for the chips to drive so quickly  so you always see a bit of the previous channel.    (2) For a board this size  I would have made the power traces much wider.  I would have made as much of the bottom of the board a solid ground plane as possible  and used wide traces for +5V.   >>    misc notes from me:    (1) i've measured the capacitance through the ni cable to the pc -- 160pF. this is within spec  but a bit high re: Reid point #1 on crosstalk above.  (2) i measured fast settle low time out of the MCU -- about 0.5s. Reid thinks this is fine.

Subject: Need a vibrating motor assembly
Question: Microscope illumination fiber needs to be vibrated to cause the internal light to be randomly reflected inside the fiber. The lab has constructed a device that has a vibrating motor assembly suspended using long elastic bands. The lab selected vibrator motors from consumer product electric toothbrushes and wired two together. The fiber is looped in a figure 8 pattern with the crossing co-located with the vibrator motor. the external loops of the figure 8 are suspended and allowed all degrees of freedom. The apparatus worked well except that the lifetime of the motors are short. The motors need to be driven with a 1-5Vdc or 1-10Vdc input to allow a variable speed. The lab would empirically determine the correct frequency for vibration.

Subject: Perfusion  fixation  cryostat sectioning of mice brains
Question: On 06/04  two mice (#AC8-1  and 9A2-3) were perfused by pump method using 4% PF in 0.0PB  and on 06/05  another AC8-1 mouse was perfused by same method after 24-hour fasting.    After overnight post-fix in 4% PF  and washed 3 times in PBS  mice brains were soaked in 30% sucrose over the weekend. Brains were sectioned by cryostat at the 25um thickness and directly mounted on slides (~ 20 slide per brain  4 sections per slide). Note: One brain was cryostat by Brenda.    Rat-HA immunostaining was performed for 2 slides from each animal by using 0.1% saponin  and 0.5% saponin. Rat-HA (dilution 1:100  made in blocking buffer: 5% BSA  5% goat serum  5% mouse serum in TBS) was used as primary antibody  and goat anti-Rat AF488 was used as secondary antibody with the dilution 1:500. TBS was used as buffer in IHC.    This project was requested on 06/03 and completed on06/10.

Subject: Perfusion and vibratome sectioning of mice brains
Question: On 06/30  three mice (#19272 with Cannula  # 19121 tag#060160  tag# 060165) were perfused by pump method using 50mL fixative (4% PF in 0.1 PB  PH=7.4). Images were taken for the whole brain   followed vibratome sectioning of brains between red signals at the thickness of 60um. After dried a couple of days  brain slices were rehydrated with PBS  then coverslipped with fluromount medium.    Issue--Brain slices looked transparent and it is hard to take image with dark field.  Trouble shooting--  1. Using extra brain slice tried two mount media: Aquamount and Fluromount  2. Tried different brain mounting process   1) Coverslipped brain slices right away after mounting on slides                                            2) Let brain slices dry then rehydrated with PBS  followed coverslipped with two media  Results:  1. Fluromount gave better contrast compared Aquamount media  2. Dry-rehydration process weakened contrast compared direct mounting    This project was requested to proceed on 06/30  and completed on 07/06/09.

Cryostat sectioning at 50 um through whole brains were followed  and brain sections were collected directly on slides with 2 seires  one is the control  one for GFP immunostaining. This step was performed by all of three members of histology  and I was involoved in cryostat sectioning for followed brains:     --07/15  cryostat sectioned mouse brain #  16154 totally 40 slides were collected   --07/20  cryostat sectioned mouse brain #  16156  totally 40 slides were collected     Immunostaing with Rb-GFP (1:2500) and Goat anti-Rb AF 488 (1:500)   --07/22  # 16154 & 16156 B series     This project was requested to proceed on 07/08 and completed on 07/23.
